Assignment 1: Exploring and Visualizing Data¶

NOTE : PLEASE DO NOT POST THE CODE OR YOUR SOLUTIONS ON THE WEB/GIT except CANVAS FOR GRADING

This assignment focuses on the EDA process where you load, explore, visualize data and present your findings.

Problem Statement : Choose a variable with meaningful magnitude and examine the effects of two transformations (scaling methods) on that variable.

Background Materials/Data : COVID 19 is an ongoing threat. Data for the outbreak are available here:
https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications-data/download-todays-data-geographic-distribution-covid-19-cases-worldwide

Using this data, you are to conduct exploratory data analysis. Provide appropriate descriptive statistics / visualizations to help understand the spread of the disease (incidence) as well as its fatality rate. You should also engage in feature creation and variable transformation. At a bare minimum, feature creation should include generating rates per X in the population (i.e., rates per million). Investigate time series as well as univariate and bivariate distribution graphs.

Select one of variable and perform both min-max and standard scaling in Python.
reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/preprocessing/plot_all_scaling.html#sphx-glr-auto-examples-preprocessing-plot-all-scaling-py

Some methods we will learn in this course (trees and random forests) are unaffected by monotonic transformations of the explanatory variables. Others (SVMs and neural networks) are very much affected by scaling and usually perform better when all explanatory variables have the same scale. It is often best to use scaling methods that preserve the shape of the distribution. But if there are extreme outliers or heavily skewed distributions, then log or normalizing transformations may be warranted.

# correlation heat map setup for seaborn
def corr_chart(df_corr):
    corr=df_corr.corr()
    #screen top half to get a triangle
    top = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=np.bool)
    top[np.triu_indices_from(top)] = True
    fig=plt.figure()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,12))
    sns.heatmap(corr, mask=top, cmap='coolwarm', 
        center = 0, square=True, 
        linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={'shrink':.5}, 
        annot = True, annot_kws={'size': 9}, fmt = '.3f')           
    plt.xticks(rotation=45) # rotate variable labels on columns (x axis)
    plt.yticks(rotation=0) # use horizontal variable labels on rows (y axis)
    plt.title('Correlation Heat Map')
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

np.set_printoptions(precision=3)

# overrides the default rcParams for plotting
def init_plotting():
    plt.style.use(style='ggplot')
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (10.0, 8.0)
    plt.rcParams['font.family'] = 'serif'
    plt.rcParams['text.color'] = 'black'
    plt.rcParams['axes.labelcolor'] = 'black'
    plt.rcParams['xtick.color']= 'black'
    plt.rcParams['ytick.color']= 'black'

init_plotting()

# avoid empty plot, always good to close plot
plt.close()

#creating new features cumCases and cumDeaths
dfus['usCumulativeCases'] = dfus['cases'].cumsum(axis = 0) 
dfus['cumulativeDeaths'] = dfus['deaths'].cumsum(axis = 0)

FINDINGS/ANALYSIS:

Questions

  • What are the management and analytical questions associated with this problem?

The management and analytical questions associated with this problem are the the covid cases for different countries. Which country's pandemic is more serious than others. What are the deaths over time for a country. The cumulative cases for a countries. The correlation between different variables in the dataset. The cases in the future.

  • What are some of the assumptions if any ?

One assumption is data set is accurate. If the dataset is not acuurate then it does not make sense to make any comparsion and analysis through dataset.

  • What are your findings/recommendations (if any) based on your analysis of the dataset?

From the early time series graph, i notice that the world covid cases continue to increase till the end of the dataset roughly 2021 - 01. Through the death time series, I notice that the deaths in the world reached the peak in april of 2020, and it is slowly decreasing. US cases continue to increase, but China reduced the new cases to nearly zero after May of 2020. Obviously, a high correlation exists between the deaths and the cases. India and US have different fatality rate peak, so this could mean the difference in the time of the spread. Using the scaler from sklean, I am able to compre the cases of different countries with different populaiton. Using the standard scaler, we can see that Belgium is better than US and India in early months, but it overtook US and india in terms of cumulative cases in later month in the dataset. From the minmaxscaler, we can see that india's cumulative cases is better than Belgium and US before September, but it overtook US nad Belgium after September. From the forcasting graph, we can see that if the pandemic is not contained and if no measures will be implementd, the cumulative caes will keep increasing exponentially.
